Lizzie made 6 batches of snicker-doodle cookies with 18 cookies per batch for a birthday party, but her hungry brother Wyatt ate 2 of the batches. To make up for the eaten cookies, Lizzie made 3 more batches with 18 cookies per batch. How many cookies does Lizzie have now?

}

\textbf{Answer:} Lizzie first made $6\cdot18$ cookies, but Wyatt ate $2\cdot18$ cookies, finally Lizzie baked $3\cdot18$ more cookies. The proper expression for this problem would be$$(6\cdot18)-(2\cdot18)+(3\cdot18)$$Now that we have a proper expression, we can rearrange the products using the commutative property and then use the distributive property to pull 18 away from the other values.\begin{align*}
(6\cdot18)-(2\cdot18)+(3\cdot18)&=(18\cdot6)-(18\cdot2)+(18\cdot3)
\\&=18\cdot(6-2+3)
\\&=18\cdot(7)
\\&=\boxed{126 \text{ cookies}}
\end{align*}
